If there were no Rule but Scripture itself for discerning among these different classeSâ€š the Conscience must often be at a loss.

And especially as these different classes are indiscriminately mixed together: for example, Levit. xix. 18. [See Elem. Moral. Art. 553]. And again, Lev. xix, 30, Ye shall keep my sabbaths, and reverence my sanctuary: I am the Lorcl. No doubt some persons hold that the former part of the precept is binding on their consciences, and that the latter is not so. But they can found such an opinion only on grounds of reason. Hence, without the Light of Reason we cannot distinguish when precepts of Scripture are obligatory.
